I have something vaguely similar in mind, but less "wow he's badass" and more of a deconstruction of that kind of hero, so common in dialup-era Internet fiction, starting with PTSD and being mostly more or less functional in between periods of crushing suicidal depression.

All possible parallel universes are real. There are extremely powerful beings--call them "gods" if you want--are fighting against powerful, intelligent entities that want to destroy all existence and all life. And they're outnumbered, losing, fighting a holding action while they try to pull a miracle out of their asses. The human--one of a small number they've chosen to fight for them--is intelligent competent, creative, resourceful, and stubborn. There are many versions of him across the parallels, fighting in a time war vast beyond human imagination. When one dies, the Gods give the survivors that one's memories, so that they can learn from his mistakes. This has poured an ocean of purified, distilled PTSD into his head along with practical knowledge about spear-and-shield fighting, piloting space fighters, maintenance and cleaning procedures for small arms from flintlock jezzails to death rays, the habits of many nonhuman intelligent species. One result of this is that he has a lot of moments where he's not sure where (or when) he is right now, and periods of crushing suicidal depression, though the Gods won't let him die, because they need him--and this should illustrate how dire the situation is. He is useful to them because he loves a good fight, much more so than is healthy. He is mentally very unwell, and from time to time other characters talking to him get glimpses.
